SCHEDULE I

Program Description

The objective of the Program is to improve quality of care, strengthen management of
NCDs and injuries, and reduce inequities in reproductive and child health services in Tamil Nadu.

The Program consists of the following parts:

Part A. Improved Quality of Care

1. Improvement in governance, through development of clinical protocols, guidelines.
monitoring of quality of care using facility dashboards, introduction and scaling up of
clinical governance and other quality improvement initiatives, and facility certification.

2. Support for certification of Primary Care Facilities and Secondary Care Facilities by
NQAS. and of Tertiary Care Facilities by NABH.

3. Expansion of continuous medical education program, and development of user-friendly
decision support tools for providers.

4. Engagement with the population, through developing and implementing patient experience
questionnaires, making quality and other data accessible to the public, and conducting
district and state health assemblies.

Part B. Strengthened Management of NCDs and Injuries

1. Improved management of NCDs, through support for:

(a) health promotion and NCD prevention, including development and implementation
of comprehensive social and behavior change communication strategy;

(b) population-based screening of NCDs, including through house visits and awareness-
raising;

(c) treatment and follow-up, including through establishment of health and wellness
centers, strengthening of Primary Health Centers, strengthening of lab services; and
strengthening of health provider capacity to address mental health;

(d) improved monitoring and evaluation, including through development of NCD care
cascades for selected tracer conditions and strengthening data on NCDs; and

(e) establishment of a multi-sectoral coordination mechanism to support state NCD
response.

2. Improved management of injuries by strengthening pre-hospital and in-hospital care,
including through:

(a) implementation of work plan for emergency medical services, including
strengthening of ambulance service, provision of 24x7 trauma care services and
establishment of a trauma registry. and

(b) training of emergency department trauma care providers and other health care
workers.

Part C. Reduced Equity Gaps in Reproductive and Child Health

1. Improving provision of reproductive and child health services.

2. Establishing maternity stay wards in remote areas.

3. Developing and implementing a social and behavior change communication strategy
tailored to Priority Districts.

Part D. Cross-Cutting Initiatives to Strengthen Institutional and State Capacity to Achieve
the Above Results

I. Strengthening the content, quality. accessibility and use of data and evidence for decision-
making, including through strengthening of HMIS, and support for operational research,
implementation research and health system research.

2. Enhancing transparency and accountability in health sector operation, including through
annual district and state health assemblies.

3. Strengthening of health administration and management, including improving integration
and coordination among health directorates and between centrally-sponsored schemes and
state-financed efforts.
SCHEDULE 2

Program Execution

Section I. Implementation Arran2ements

A. Institutional Arrangements

1I To facilitate the carrying out of the Program, the Borrower shall make the proceeds of the
Loan available to the Program Implementing Entity in accordance with the Borrower's
standard arrangements for developmental assistance to the states of India. Notwithstanding
the foregoing, in the event that any provision of this Agreement, including the instructions
that the Bank shall have specified by notice to the Borrower pursuant to Section 2.01(b) of
the General Conditions (including the Disbursement and Financial Information Letter),,
were to be found inconsistent with the Borrower's standard arrangements for development
assistance to the states of India, the provisions of this Agreement and aforesaid instructions
shall govern.

2. The Borrower shall at all times protect its own interests and the interests of the Bank to
accomplish the purposes of the Loan.

B. Program Action Plan

1 . The Borrower shall cause the Program Implementing Entity to:

(a) implement the Program Action Plan agreed with the Bank, in a manner and
substance satisfactory to the Bank and

(b) refrain from amending, revising, waiving, voiding, suspending or abrogating, any
provision of the Program Action Plan, whether in whole or in part, without the
prior written concurrence of the Bank.

2. In the event of any inconsistency between the provision of the Program Action Plan and
those of this Agreement and/or the Program Agreement, the provision of the latter
agreement(s) shall govern.

C. Fiduciary, Environmental and Social Systems for the Program

Without limitation on the provisions of Article V of the General Conditions, the Borrower
shall cause the Program Implementing Entity to carry out the Program in accordance with
financial management, procurement and environmental and social management systems
acceptable to the Bank, including those set out in the ESSA and the Program Action Plan
("Program Fiduciary, Environmental and Social Systems") which are designed to ensure
that:

(a) the Loan proceeds are used for their intended purposes, with due attention to the
principles of economy, efficiency, effectiveness, transparency, and accountability;
and

(b) the actual and potential adverse environmental and social impacts of the Program
are identified, avoided, minimized, or mitigated, as the case may be, all through an
informed decision-making process.

Section I. Excluded Activities

The Borrower shall, through the Program Implementing Entity. ensure that the Program
excludes any activities which:

(a) in the opinion of the Bank, are likely to have significant adverse impacts that are
sensitive, diverse, or unprecedented on the environment and!or affected people; or

(b) involve the procurement of: (1) works, estimated to cost USD 115,000,000
equivalent or more per contract: (2) goods, and non-consulting services, estimated
to cost USD 75,000,000 equivalent or more per contract; or (3) consulting services,
estimated to cost USD 30,000,000 equivalent or more per contract.

Section M. Program Monitorinz, Reporting and Evaluation

A. Program Reports

The Borrower shall cause the Program Implementing Entity to furnish to the Bank each
Program Report not later than two months after the end of each fiscal semester, covering
the fiscal semester.

B. Verification Protocols

The Borrower shall cause the Program Implementing Entity to:

(a) undertake a verification process. in accordance with the terms of reference agreed
with the Bank, to certify the fulfillment of the Disbursement Linked Results
(DLRs) set out in Schedule 3 to this Agreement; and

(b) furnish to the Bank corresponding verification report(s), in form and substance
agreed with the Bank.

